    <name>
				<text>1.2.2.5  Simplify indices</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise <br></p>

<p>Simplify, leaving your answer in the simplest form:</p>

<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li><p>\({@a1@}x^{@a2@}(x^{@a3@})=\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p></li>

<li><p>\({@b1@}x^{@b3@}({@b2@}x)=\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]</p></li>

<li><p>\({@c1@}x^{-1}({@c2@}x^{@c3@})= \) [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]</p></li>

<li><p>\({@d1@}x(x^{@d2@})=\) [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]</p></li>
</ol>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<ol class="HELM_parts">
    <li>
      <p>Removing the brackets and using the first law of indices we get:</p>
      <p>\( {@a1@}x^{@a2@}(x^{@a3@}) = {@a1@} \cdot x^{{@a2@}+{@a3@}} = {@ta1@}.\)</p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>Multiplying like terms and using the first law of indices we get:</p>
      <p>\( {@b1@}x^{@b3@}({@b2@}x) = {@b1@} \cdot {@b2@} \cdot x^{@b3@} \cdot x = {@b1@} \cdot {@b2@} \cdot x^{{@b3@}+1} = {@ta2@} .\)</p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>Similarly, \({@c1@}x^{-1}({@c2@}x^{@c3@})= {@c1@} \cdot {@c2@} \cdot x^{-1} \cdot x^{@c3@} = {@c1@} \cdot {@c2@} \cdot x^{{@c3@} - 1} = {@ta3@}. \)</p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>Again, we obtain: \( {@d1@}x(x^{@d2@})= {@d1@} \cdot x^{1+{@d2@}} = {@ta4@}.\)</p>
    </li>
</ol>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
